## Bottom line

LCES is an unusually forceful attempt to turn legal disorder into a disciplined sequence: isolate the issue, anchor the facts, define the objective, research before drafting, separate drafting from critique, and treat preservation as part of the remedy. In the context of the justice gap, large numbers of self-represented litigants, and growing AI-assisted filing, that is a serious and timely idea. The framework deserves attention as a procedural-literacy model and as a potential teaching and clinic workflow. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn22view1Ņłéturn22view2Ņłéturn26view0Ņłéturn12view3Ņłü

What the current evidence does **not** yet show is that LCES is a validated, user-tested, court-integrated system on the level of mature guided-interview ecosystems. To reach that level, the project would need the kinds of evaluation that NCSC and Stanford recommend for self-help tools: measurable effects on user comprehension, task completion, filing quality, rejection rates, accessibility, preservation completeness, and downstream outcomes. Until that kind of evidence exists, the fairest conclusion is that LCES is a promising workflow architecture and educational framework, but not yet a proven substitute for the institutional rigor of established access-to-justice infrastructure or licensed counsel. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn22view0Ņłéturn23view2Ņłéturn23view1Ņłü